{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bc4f2075-2e76-461f-a792-8cf24ee96718","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Collect the trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p $(pgrep -f dotnet) --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**3. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**4. Analyze** in Visual Studio, VS Code (`.NET Profile Visualizer` extension), or PerfView on Windows. You can also convert to speedscope format for browser-based viewing:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool install` isn't possible (read-only filesystem), use the [standalone download](https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace) or a sidecar container.\n- For production, prefer `--duration` over manual stop to avoid forgetting a running trace.\n- `--profile cpu-sampling` is lightweight (~5% overhead) and safe for production.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fe55b4fa-299d-490e-9e87-60af721cb14b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I'll provide concise, practical guidance.","outputTokens":392,"requestId":"2C42:152429:2848FDF:2C9BC27:69F9475A"},"id":"f7280685-60ee-4d36-91e8-69f7f44ca992","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:27:01.034Z","parentId":"24086feb-a5ba-4501-a951-b4d12bd0f7b7"}
